frameDefinitions: An Agent acts to ensure that a Rule (often a constraint on behavior) is being followed.
A Law regulates activities or states of affairs within a Jurisdiction, dictating what Required states should be the case and what Forbidden states should not.
A Duty is imposed on a Responsible_party according to a Principle which regulates how the Responsible_party should respond to a Situation.
An Agent schedules an Event to take place at a specified Scheduled_time and Place.
In this frame, an Authority allows a Protagonist to know (in some way) that they may or may not engage in an Action.
In this frame a State_of_affairs is prohibited (or allowed) by a Principle.
frameExamples: Why don't we <t>enforce</t> the 20000 gun laws currently on the books across the nation?
The new <t>act</t> banning smoking in public will pass soon.
They escaped total Soviet invasion and occupation only by entering into a separate agreement that <t>obligated</t> them to military action against the retreating German armies.
Gina <t>scheduled</t> a dentist appointment for Monday in Berkeley.
The police officer <t>forbid</t> me from turning around .
listRoleDefinitions: The <fen>Rule</fen> is the set of constrants on behavior that the <fen>Agent</fen> implements (i.e., forces others to obey or face consequences).
The <fen>Agent</fen>, often an institution, governmental organization, or arm thereof, puts into effect (i.e., enforces) a <fen>Rule</fen>.
This role describes the medium through which the rule was enforced.  It may occur in the same syntactic position as the Agent.
The <fen>Time</fen> at which the Agent enforces the <fen>Rule</fen>.
The <fen>Place</fen> at which the <fen>Rule</fen> is or is not enforced.
This role identifies the rule designed to guide activity, deprecating some types of activity and/or requiring other types of activity. This role is incorporated into each LU in this frame.
The state-of-affairs which is disallowed by the <fen>Law</fen>.
A state-of-affairs which the <fen>Law</fen> declares must be maintained.
The person who must perform the <fen>Duty</fen>.
The action that the <fen>Responsible_party</fen> is obligated to perform.
The <fen>Obligator</fen> is the person who imposes the <fen>Duty</fen> on the <fen>Responsible_party</fen>.
A state of affairs that results in the <fen>Responsible_party</fen> being obligated to carry out the <fen>Duty</fen> in accordance with the <fen>Principle</fen>.
A regulating idea  (which may be instantiated as a document)  that the <fen>Responsible_party</fen> is subject to.
The time interval during which  the <fen>Duty</fen> is imposed on the <fen>Responsible_party</fen>  by the <fen>Obligator</fen> or the <fen>Situation</fen>.
A location in which the <fen>Responsible_party</fen> has a specified <fen>Duty</fen> .
The sentient being who schedules an <fen>Event</fen> to take place at a <fen>Time</fen> and <fen>Place</fen>.
The incident that the <fen>Agent</fen> has scheduled to take place at a <fen>Time</fen> and <fen>Place</fen>.
The time at which the <fen>Event</fen> is scheduled to take place.
This role describes the time at which the scheduling occurs.
The location where the <fen>Agent</fen> has scheduled the <fen>Event</fen> to take place.
The <fen>Authority</fen> orders the <fen>Protagonist</fen> to not engage in a particular <fen>Action</fen>.
The <fen>Protagonist</fen> wants to engage in an <fen>Action</fen>, but is ordered not to by the <fen>Authority</fen>.
The <fen>Action</fen> is what the <fen>Protagonist</fen> seeks to do, but is ordered not to.
The <fen>Time</fen> is when the denying of permission occurs.
The <fen>Place</fen> is where the denial of permission occurs.
A moral, legal, or social norm which rules a <fen>State_of_affairs</fen> to be inadmissible behavior or an outcome of behavior.
The <fen>Time</fen> is when the prohibiting occurs.
The <fen>Place</fen> is where the prohibiting occurs.
listRoleExamples: Employers should strictly enforce <fex>a prohibition against use of any substance that may affect a worker's physical or mental ability</fex>.
Can <fex>a landlord</fex> enforce rules upon tenants?
The rules will be enforced <fex>by a new computer system that tracks people's movements</fex>.
That particular regulation was only enforced <fex>in 1920</fex>.
For this reason they enforced the settlement system <fex>in America</fex> just as strictly as in Germany.
I think we need a law <fex>against all firearms within city limits</fex>.
The law <fex>that all minors must be accompanied by an adult</fex> is a laughingstock.
The winning bid committed <fex>her</fex> to paint an oil portrait for the high bidder.

Had she really said the word which pledged her <fex>to marry Horace Holmcroft in a
fortnight</fex>?
<fex>She</fex> pledged him to pay her the money back.
<fex>Admitting a genocide was occurring</fex>  would have obligated them, based on their signing the December 1948 Convention on the repression of genocide, to do something about it.
And <fex>no law</fex> obligated him to talk to the police, let alone the media

The City Council <fex>then</fex> obligated themselves to have the sewers made ready and the
streets leveled off without any additional cost to the Sisters.
<fex>At Dayton</fex>, the parties obligated themselves to respect and promote fulfillment of the annexes.
<fex>I</fex> set up a meeting with Carlos on Monday.
I'd like to set up <fex>a meeting with Mr. Hofmann</fex>.
Gina scheduled a dentist appointment for Monday <fex>in Berkeley</fex>.

<fex>The Establishment Clause of the First Amendment</fex> plainly prohibits the
establishment of a national religion by Congress.
